fields.text:
So basically, I got into uoft comp sci and ever since my dad heard of it, he's been raving on about me upgrading my old, worn down, shitty, laptop with a nice, new, expensive one. The thing is, I've formed an emotional attachment to rudy (my laptop's nickname), and I don't wanna get rid of my little soldier.

Rudy is a lenovo ideapad 710s. He's a 13 inch grower with an i7 6th gen, 8gb ddr4 ram (soldered on, no upgrades), 256gb nvme ssd upgradeable, and a cpu with nice new thermal paste. The laptop's condition is good, since i've basically fixed every issue it's had like replacing hinges, screen and speaker. Webcam, mic, trackpad, keyboard, usb ports, other connections and everything important still work like a charm. The battery is old and needs replacing but that'll cost me only 40 bucks and i'll get 8 hrs of battery life. Hell, even the design is still holding up great, with super thin bezels and a sleek and thin design. Mf can fit into anything.

Sure the specs dont sound the best, and I could be better off laying rudy to rest, but there's more to this laptop. I've had this bad boy since grade 6, and it has served me faithfully ever since. It taught me more than i'd ever learn. and I feel like i'd be betraying rudy if I replaced it when the going got tough. It's exactly like when griffith ascended into a god, leaving guts and the band of the hawks behind. I can't turn into a griffith.

Plus I feel like the thousands of $ spent on a new laptop could be better spent on something nicer, like a cool lil car or a bike, instead of a foldable computer that'll over heat whenever you push the thing to its limits.

So, is rudy good enough to do comp sci work at uoft? Or do I have to say goodbye to an old friend and retire him.

Thanks!

Yes, I’d say most courses are pretty simple and straight forward. All you need is to pay attention to lectures and have some common sense. Most STEM concepts are pretty straight forward, specially in undergrad. I’d say everything but MAT and STA courses are just common sense, and as long as you understand pre-requisite material you’re good. Don’t make material harder than it has to be by digging deeper and deeper, learn what’s taught and if you want to go deeper into it, take upper year courses related to it and/or do a masters related to whatever intrigues you.
